{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180821182325|855919868","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Alcee_Hastings","to":"Alcee Hastings"}],"pages":{"411264":{"pageid":411264,"ns":0,"title":"Alcee Hastings","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-03T10:07:05Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Alcee Hastings\n|image        = Alcee Hastings Portrait c111-112th Congress.jpg\n|state        = [[Florida]]\n|district     = {{ushr|FL|20|20th}}\n|prior_term   = {{ushr|FL|23|23rd}} (1993\u20132013)\n|term_start   = January 3, 1993\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = Constituency established\n|successor    =\n|office1      = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]]\n|term_start1  = November 2, 1979\n|term_end1    = October 20, 1989\n|nominator1   =\n|appointer1   = [[List of federal judges appointed by Jimmy Carter|Jimmy Carter]]\n|predecessor1 = ''Seat established by 92 Stat. 1629''\n|successor1   = [[Federico A. Moreno]]\n|birth_name   = Alcee Lamar Hastings\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1936|09|05}}\n|birth_place  = [[Altamonte Springs, Florida|Altamonte Springs]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[Fisk University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br>{{nowrap|[[Howard University School of Law]]}}<br>[[Florida A&M University College of Law]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n}}\n'''Alcee Lamar Hastings''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|l|s|i\u02d0}} (born September 5, 1936) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Florida|20}}. The district includes most of the majority-black precincts in and around [[Fort Lauderdale]] and [[West Palm Beach]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he served as a [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]] until his impeachment and removal.<ref name=\"Senate Removes Hastings\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/campaigns/junkie/links/hastings102189.htm Senate Removes Hastings], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', October 21, 1989. Retrieved March 14, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\n\nBorn in [[Altamonte Springs, Florida|Altamonte Springs]], [[Florida]], Hastings was educated at  [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] and [[Fisk University]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]].{{sfn|''Congressional Directory 2005\u20132006: One Hundred Ninth Congress''|page=68}} He earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[zoology]] and [[botany]] from Fisk in 1958.{{sfn|''Congressional Directory 2005\u20132006: One Hundred Ninth Congress''|page=68}} He attended [[Howard University School of Law]] from 1958 to 1960, and received his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Florida A&M University College of Law]] in 1963.{{sfn|''Congressional Directory 2005\u20132006: One Hundred Ninth Congress''|page=68}} While in school, he became a member of the [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity. He was admitted to the bar in 1963, and began to [[Practice of law|practice law]].{{sfn|''Congressional Directory 2005\u20132006: One Hundred Ninth Congress''|page=68}}\n\n===1970 U.S. Senate election===\n\n{{See also|United States Senate elections, 1970}}\nHastings decided to run for [[United States Senate]] in 1970 after incumbent [[Spessard Holland]] decided to retire. He failed to win the Democratic primary, or make the run-off election. He ranked fourth out of five candidates, receiving 13% of the vote. Governor [[Farris Bryant]] ranked first with 33% of the vote. [[Lawton Mainor Chiles, Jr.|Lawton Chiles]] ranked second with 26% of the vote. Chiles defeated Bryant in the run-off election and won the November general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=236084|title=Our Campaigns - FL US Senate - D Primary Race - Sep 08, 1970|website=www.ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career (1977\u20131989)==\n\nIn 1977, Hastings became a judge of the circuit court of [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]], Florida.\n\nHastings was nominated by President [[Jimmy Carter]] on August 28, 1979, to the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]], to a new seat authorized by 92 Stat. 1629. He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on October 31, 1979, and received his commission on November 2, 1979. His service was terminated on October 20, 1989, due to impeachment and conviction.\n\n===Allegations and impeachment===\n\nIn 1981, Hastings was charged with accepting a $150,000 bribe in exchange for a lenient sentence and a return of seized assets for 21 counts of [[racketeering]] by Frank and Thomas Romano, and of perjury in his testimony about the case. In 1983, he was acquitted by a jury after his alleged co-conspirator, William Borders, refused to testify in court, resulting in a jail sentence for Borders.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fW8aAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5CkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3890,2277600&dq=alcee+hastings+acquitted \"Federal Judge Acquitted\"] ''Milwaukee Journal'', Feb. 4, 1983</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the Democratic-controlled [[United States House of Representatives]] took up the case, and Hastings was [[Impeachment in the United States|impeached]] for bribery and [[perjury]] by a vote of 413\u20133. He was then convicted on October 20, 1989 by the [[United States Senate]], becoming the sixth federal judge in the history of the [[impeachment in the United States|United States]] to be removed from office by the Senate. The Senate, in two hours of roll calls, voted on 11 of the 17 articles of impeachment. It convicted Hastings of eight of the 11 articles. The vote on the first article was 69 for and 26 opposed.<ref name=\"Senate Removes Hastings\"/>\n\nThe Senate had the option to forbid Hastings from ever seeking federal office again, but did not do so. Alleged co-conspirator attorney William Borders went to jail again for refusing to testify in the impeachment proceedings, but was later given a full pardon by President [[Bill Clinton]] on his last day in office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1066080426784 |title=The Power of the Pardon |publisher=Law.com |date=2011-07-15 |accessdate=2011-07-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090216112646/http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1066080426784| archivedate=February 16, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>\n\nHastings filed suit in federal court claiming that his impeachment trial was invalid because he was tried by a Senate committee, not in front of the full Senate, and that he had been acquitted in a criminal trial. Judge [[Stanley Sporkin]] ruled in favor of Hastings, remanding the case to the Senate, but stayed his ruling pending the outcome of an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in a similar case regarding Judge [[Walter Nixon]], who had also been impeached and removed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/campaigns/junkie/links/hastings091892.htm |title=Senate Conviction of Hastings Is Reversed by Judge Sporkin |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=1992-09-18 |accessdate=2011-07-22}}</ref>\n\nSporkin found some \"crucial distinctions\"<ref>''[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?q=Hastings+v.+U.S.,+802+F.Supp.+490&hl=en&as_sdt=6,37&case=15535651293027319741&scilh=0 Hastings v. U.S., 802 F.Supp. 490]''</ref> between Nixon's case and Hastings', specifically, that Nixon had been convicted criminally, and that Hastings was not found guilty by two-thirds of the committee who actually \"tried\" his impeachment in the Senate. He further added that Hastings had a right to trial by the full Senate.\n\nThe Supreme Court, however, ruled in ''[[Nixon v. United States]]'' that the federal courts have no jurisdiction over Senate impeachment matters, so Sporkin's ruling was vacated and Hastings's conviction and removal were upheld.<ref>''[http://www.leagle.com/decision/1993840837FSupp3_1839.xml HASTINGS v. U.S.]'' 837 F.Supp. 3 (1993)</ref>\n\n==1990 Secretary of State election==\n\nHastings attempted to make a political comeback by running for [[Secretary of State of Florida]], campaigning on a platform of legalizing [[casino]]s. In a three-way Democratic primary, he placed second with 33% of the vote, behind newspaper columnist Jim Minter's 38% of the vote. In the [[runoff election|runoff]], which saw a large dropoff in turnout, Minter defeated him, 67%\u201333%. He won just one of [[List of counties in Florida|Florida's 67 counties]]: [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=376672|title=Our Campaigns - FL Secretary of State - D Runoff Race - Oct 02, 1990|website=www.ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> Minter went on to lose in the general election to incumbent Republican [[James C. Smith]].\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1993\u2013present)==\n\n===Elections===\n\nHastings was elected to the United States House of Representatives in 1992, representing [[Florida's 23rd congressional district|Florida's 23rd district]]. After placing second in the initial Democratic primary for the post, he scored an upset victory over state representative [[Lois J. Frankel]] in the runoff and went on to easily win election in the heavily-Democratic district. From that point on he has yet to face a serious challenge for reelection. Subsequent to redistricting and the 2012 election, Alcee Hastings represents [[Florida's 20th congressional district|Florida's 20th district]] beginning January 2013.\n\n===Tenure===\n\nHastings is a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> and was elected president of the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe|Parliamentary Assembly]] of the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] in July 2004. Today, as a senior Democratic whip, Hastings is an influential member of the Democratic leadership. Hastings is also a member of the powerful [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] and is a senior member of the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]] (HPSCI). On the HPSCI, Hastings is the chairman of the Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations.\n\nHe was one of the 31 who voted in the House not to count the [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral votes]] from [[Ohio]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 presidential election]].<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2005/roll007.xml</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050112072650/http://clerk.house.gov:80/evs/2005/roll007.xml|title=109 1st U.S. House of Representatives MOTION On Agreeing to the Objection|last=|first=|date=2005-01-12|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref>\n\nHastings voted to impeach Texas federal judge [[Samuel B. Kent]] on all four counts presented against him on June 19, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/index.asp |title=U.S. House of Representatives Roll Call Votes |publisher=Clerk.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Bid for chairmanship of the House Intelligence Committee===\n\nAfter the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2006|2006 United States House of Representatives elections]], Hastings attracted attention after it was reported that incoming [[U.S. Speaker of the House|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] might appoint him as head of the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]. He had support from the [[Congressional Black Caucus]], but was opposed by the [[Blue Dog Coalition]]. Hastings attacked his critics as \u201cmisinformed fools.\u201d Pelosi reportedly favored Hastings instead of the ranking Democrat [[Jane Harman]] due to policy differences and support by the Congressional Black Caucus.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15741999/ns/politics-tom_curry/t/battle-hastings-adds-pelosi-drama/#.T2IOhHngFv0  Battle of Hastings adds to Pelosi drama] MSNBC, Nov. 16, 2006</ref> On November 28, 2006, Pelosi announced that Hastings would not be the Committee's chairman,<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6550628 Pelosi Shuts Hastings Out of Intel Chairmanship] NPR, Nov. 28, 2006</ref> and later she chose [[Silvestre Reyes]] (D-TX) instead. While Hastings was passed over to chair the committee, he became chair of a sub-committee. He told the [[National Journal]] that \u201cI am not angry. At some point along the way, it became too much to explain. That is legitimate politics. But it\u2019s unfortunate for me.\u201d<ref>http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/alcee-hastings-fl/</ref>\n\n===Comments about Sarah Palin===\n\nOn September 24, 2008, Hastings came under fire for comments he made regarding [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] vice-presidential candidate [[Sarah Palin]]. Hastings, speaking in [[Washington D.C.]] to a conference sponsored by the [[National Jewish Democratic Council]], said \"If Sarah Palin isn't enough of a reason for you to get over whatever your problem is with [[Barack Obama]], then you damn well had better pay attention. Anybody toting guns and stripping moose don't care too much about what they do with Jews and blacks. So, you just think this through.\" <ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Rigel  |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2008/09/florida-congres/ |title=Florida Congressman: Palin 'Don't Care Too Much What They Do With Jews and Blacks' \u2013 Political Radar |publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=2008-09-24 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 2008, Hastings issued an apology via a written statement, while standing by its core message: \"I regret the comments I made last Tuesday that were not smart and certainly not relevant to hunters or sportsmen. The point I made, and will continue to make, is that the policies and priorities of a McCain-Palin administration would be anathema to most African Americans and Jews. I regret that I was not clearer and apologize to Governor Palin, my host where I was speaking, and those who my comments may have offended.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/09/29/black-florida-congressman-apologizes-for-comments-about-palin/ | work=CNN | title=Black Florida congressman apologizes for Palin comments | accessdate=April 23, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100324180833/http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/09/29/black-florida-congressman-apologizes-for-comments-about-palin/| archivedate= 24 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no | date=2008-09-29}}</ref>\n\n===Lexus lease===\n\nIn May 2009, the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Hastings spent over $24,000 in taxpayer money in 2008 to lease a luxury [[Lexus Hybrid Drive|Lexus hybrid sedan]]. The ''Journal'' noted that the expenditure was legal, properly accounted for, and drawn from an expense allowance the U.S. government grants to all lawmakers.<ref>{{cite news|first=Louise |last=Radnofsky |author2=Farnam, T.W. |title=Lawmakers Bill Taxpayers For TVs, Cameras, Lexus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124364352135868189 |work=Wall Street Journal|date=May 30, 2009 |accessdate=2009-06-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608015318/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB124364352135868189.html |archivedate=8 June 2009 |deadurl=no }}\n</ref>\n\n===Comments about Affordable Care Act legislation===\n\nIn March 2010, Hastings defended Democrats\u2019 approach to passing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], saying \"I wish that I had been there when [[Thomas Edison]] made the remark that I think applies here: 'There ain't no rules around here, we're trying to accomplish something.' And therefore, when the deal goes down, all this talk about rules, we make them up as we go along.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://postonpolitics.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2010/03/20/rep-alcee-hastings-invokes-thomas-edison-no-rules-around-here-were-trying-to-accomplish-something/ |title=Rep. Alcee Hastings invokes Thomas Edison: \u2018No rules around here \u2014 we\u2019re trying to accomplish something\u2019 |publisher=Post on Politics |date=2010-03-20 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment allegation===\n\nIn June 2011, a lawsuit filed by one of his staff members, Winsome Packer, alleged that Hastings made repeated unwanted sexual advances and threatened her job when she refused him.<ref name=ethics/> A congressional ethics panel investigated these claims.<ref name=ethics>{{cite news|last=Fields |first=Gary| first2=Brody|last2=Mullins|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304887904576400053258305010 |title=Florida Congressman Faces New Ethics Review|publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=2011-06-22 |accessdate=2011-07-22}}</ref> Packer was being represented by the conservative legal group [[Judicial Watch]]. Hastings denied the claims and called them \"ludicrous.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/22/alcee-hastings-sexual-harassment_n_882251.html?icid=maing-grid7%7Cmain5%7Cdl1%7Csec3_lnk1%7C72410 |title=Alcee Hastings Sexual Harassment Allegation Investigated By Ethics Panel |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2011-06-22|accessdate=2011-07-22 |first=Simon |last=McCormack}}</ref> He stated that \"I will win this lawsuit. That is a certainty. In a race with a lie, the truth always wins. And when the truth comes to light and the personal agendas of my accusers are exposed, I will be vindicated.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.lalate.com/2011/03/10/winsome-packer-claims-alcee-hastings-harassment-in-lawsuit/|title=Winsome Packer Claims Alcee Hastings Harassment in Lawsuit|website=news.lalate.com}}</ref> In February 2012, it was reported that Hastings would be released from the lawsuit, and it would only continue against the [[Commission on Security and Cooperation in Europe|Helsinki Commission]] which Hastings chaired and Packer represented in Vienna.<ref name=\"Harassment Lawsuit\">{{cite news|title=Alcee Hastings Released From Personal Liability In Sexual Harassment Lawsuit|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/14/alcee-hastings-sexual-harassment-lawsuit_n_1277369.html|accessdate=6 July 2012|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=14 February 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216072106/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/14/alcee-hastings-sexual-harassment-lawsuit_n_1277369.html|archivedate=16 February 2012}}</ref> In December 2017, it was reported that the Treasury Department paid $220,000 to settle the lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/alcee-hastings-sexual-harassment|title=Exclusive: Taxpayers Paid $220K to Settle Case Involving Rep. Alcee Hastings|last=Akin|first=Stephanie|date=2017-12-09|work=Roll Call|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\n===Least wealthy congressman===\n\nIn a 2011 survey of U.S. lawmakers, the [[Center for Responsive Politics]] named Hastings the \"Poorest Member of Congress,\" with a 2010 average net worth of {{nowrap|\u2212$4,732,002}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/25-richest-members-of-congress/2011/07/11/gIQAmtxiMK_gallery.html?hpid=z2#photo=52 |title=Richest and 'poorest' Members of Congress|publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=2011-12-30 |accessdate=2011-12-30}}</ref> His congressional financial disclosure form indicated that, as of 2010, Hastings did not have any earned income, he had a bank account with a balance in the $1,000 to $15,000 range, and he owed several million dollars in legal fees to several attorneys stemming from the 1981\u20131989 charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/public_disc/financial-pdfs/2011/8202579.pdf|title=Calendar Year 2010 Financial Disclosure Statement, The Hon. Alcee Lamar Hastings}}</ref>\n\n===Nepotism claims===\n\nIn 2012, Hastings was ranked 1 out of 435 members of the U.S. House of Representatives for paying salaries and fees to family members, according to the conservative watchdog group, [[Judicial Watch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/blog/2012/03/alcee-hastings-ranks-no-1-in-nepotism/|title=Alcee Hastings Ranks No.1 In Nepotism   - Judicial Watch|date=27 March 2012|publisher=}}</ref> A state by state report on all members of Congress, published by the [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]], reported Hastings paid his girlfriend, Patricia Williams, an attorney who worked as his deputy district director, $622,574 over the four-year period, from 2007\u20132010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family_Affair_House_2012_CREW.pdf?nocdn%3D1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014033603/http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family_Affair_House_2012_CREW.pdf?nocdn=1 |archivedate=2014-10-14 |df= }}</ref>  \n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== 2016 congressional election ===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2016#District 20}}\nHastings won the general election on November 8, 2016, defeating Republican Gary Stein, by a margin of 80.3% to 19.7%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Florida's_20th_Congressional_District_election,_2016|title=Florida's 20th Congressional District election, 2016 - Ballotpedia|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Rules|Committee on Rules]]'''\n** [[United States House Rules Subcommittee on Legislative and Budget Process|Subcommittee on Legislative and Budget Process]] (Ranking member)\n* '''[[Commission on Security and Cooperation in Europe]]''' (Ranking member)\n\n=== Leadership positions ===\n\n* Florida Congressional delegation (co-chairman)\n* Senior Democratic whip\n* [[Congressional Caucus on Global Road Safety]] (co-chairman)\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n* Sportsmen's Caucus\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|title=Membership|author=|date=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|format=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Afterschool Caucuses]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/policyCongressionalCaucuses.cfm|title=Members|author=|date=|publisher=Afterschool Alliance|format=|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|title=Members|author=|date=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|format=|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|title=Our Members|author=|date=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus|format=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gun policy===\n\nHastings has stated that gun control is a \"critical element\" of addressing the United States' crime problem.<ref name=\"Hastings\">{{cite web|url=https://alceehastings.house.gov/issues/issue/?IssueID=100704| website=U. S. Congressman Alcee L. Hastings| publisher=U. S. Federal Government|title=Gun Control| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nHastings is favor of reinstating the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].\nHe also supports a federal ban on [[Bump fire#Bump fire stocks|bump stocks]].\nHe supports raising the minimum age to buy a rifle from 18 to 21.\nIn 2017, he voted against the [[Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act of 2017]].\nHis current rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] is an \"F\", indicating that it believes he does not support gun rights legislation.<ref name=\"Daugherty 2018\">{{cite news| url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article201204999.html| title=Where South Floridians in Congress stand on gun legislatio| last=Daugherty| first=Alex| date=20 February 2018| work=Miami Herald| location=Miami, Florida| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2018 [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], Hastings released a statement in which he said, \"The stranglehold of the gun lobby has gone on long enough.\"<ref name=\"Hastings 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://alceehastings.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398938Hastings\u2019|title=Statement on Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School Shooting|last=|first=|date=14 February 2018|website=U. S. Congressman Alcee L. Hastings|publisher=U. S. Federal Government|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nHastings wrote a letter to the Speaker of the Florida House and President of the Florida Senate urging them to repeal the state's [[Gun laws in Florida#Preemption|Preemption law]], which prohibits communities in Florida from passing their own gun regulations.<ref name=\"Hastings 2018b\">{{cite web| url=https://alceehastings.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398943| title=Hastings Urges Florida State Legislature to Repeal Firearm Preemption Law| date=27 February 2018| website=U. S. Congressman Alcee L. Hastings| publisher=U. S. Federal Government| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |last=U.S. House of Representatives |date=2005 |title=Congressional Directory 2005\u20132006: One Hundred Ninth Congress |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kl_GqvpDelsC&pg=PA68 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |isbn=978-0-16-072467-1 |ref={{sfnRef|''Congressional Directory 2005-2006: One Hundred Ninth Congress''}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|c=Category:Alcee Hastings|d=Q1758631|s=Author:Alcee_Lamar_Hastings|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|q=no}}\n* [https://alceehastings.house.gov/ Congressman Alcee Hastings] official U.S. House website\n* [http://alceeforcongress.com/ Alcee Hastings for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Alcee_Hastings_%5BD-20%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|alceehastings}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=h000324 | votesmart=26798 | fec=H2FL23021 | congress=alcee-hastings/H000324 }}\n* {{FJC Bio|996|nid=1381916|name=Alcee Lamar Hastings<!--(1936\u2013)-->}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=Seat established by 92 Stat. 1629}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]]}}|years=1979\u20131989}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Federico A. Moreno]]}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Florida's 23rd congressional district]]|years=1993\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. Ho